Think of a Callable as a Runnable that can "talk back."
While a Runnable just performs a task and finishes (like a fire-and-forget mission), a Callable performs a task and returns a result or throws an exception.
The Core Difference
| Feature | Runnable | Callable |
|---|---|---|
| Method | run() | call() |
| Return Value | void (Nothing) | V (Any object you specify) |
| Exceptions | Cannot throw checked exceptions | Can throw checked exceptions |
1. A Basic Callable Example
Imagine you want a thread to calculate the sum of a list of numbers and give you the answer.
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;

// This Callable returns an Integer
Callable<Integer> sumTask = () -> {
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
        sum += i;
    }
    return sum; // The "Result"
};

2. Using Callable with Virtual Threads
When you submit a Callable to an executor, it doesn't give you the result immediately (because the thread is still working). Instead, it gives you a Future. Think of a Future as a "claim check" for a result that will be ready soon.
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;

public class CallableExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        
        // Define the task: Go fetch a person's name from a database
        Callable<String> fetchNameTask = () -> {
            Thread.sleep(1000); // Simulate network delay
            return "John Doe";
        };

        try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            // Submit returns a Future (the claim check)
            Future<String> claimCheck = executor.submit(fetchNameTask);

            System.out.println("Doing other work while the thread fetches the name...");

            // .get() blocks the main thread until the virtual thread is done
            String result = claimCheck.get(); 
            System.out.println("Result received: " + result);
        }
    }
}

3. How it fits your Salesforce scenario
In your case, your Callable is the bridge between your Orchestrator and your Existing Service.
// 1. You define WHAT you want to happen inside the thread
Callable<List<SyncResult>> task = () -> {
    // This calls your existing service and RETURNS the list it produces
    return salesforceService.pushBatchToSalesforce(myBatch);
};

// 2. You submit it to the virtual thread executor
Future<List<SyncResult>> future = executor.submit(task);

// 3. Later, you collect the result
List<SyncResult> results = future.get();

Why use Callable instead of Runnable?
 * Error Handling: If your Salesforce service throws an ApiException, a Callable will capture it. When you call future.get(), it will throw an ExecutionException, allowing you to handle the error in your main thread.
 * Data Flow: It is much cleaner to "return" data from a thread than to try and "write" data to a shared list from 50 different threads at once.
